File: Comair went under voluntary business rescue in May as revenues took a major hit when air travel was banned early in the lockdown. JOHANNESBURG - Local airline company Comair will again take to the skies after being offered a lifeline in the form of R1.5-billion in business rescue funding. Business rescue practitioners announced the offer from a yet-to-be-named consortium to about 200 creditors on Thursday. READ: Comair to halve its fleet The former management team will also be returning. The company, however, will delist from the Johannesburg Stock Exchange as part of its turnaround strategy. READ: Comair BRPs granted more time for plan Comair went under voluntary business rescue in May as revenues took a major hit when air travel was banned early in the lockdown. The airline says it will now resume its services on 1 December.